<h5 class="MsoNormalM"><b>Planning your onward Air flight/train/ Bus booking&nbsp;</b>















</h5>
<p class="MsoNormalM">If you are traveling from Kolkata, Bangalore, Chennai, Pune,
Mumbai, or Gujarat any other city, you will have to come to Delhi, and you will
get a train from Delhi to Dehradun comfortably.</p>

















<p class="MsoNormalM">To reach Dehradun or Rishikesh for the Brahmatal Trek, you
can follow these general guidelines. Keep in mind that transportation options
and routes might change, so it’s always a good idea to double-check closer to
your travel date.</p>

















<ol start="1">
 <li><b>Reach
     Delhi</b>: Most travelers start their journey by reaching Delhi, which is
     a major transportation hub. You can reach Delhi by air, train, or bus,
     depending on your location.</li>
 <li><b>Delhi
     to Dehradun/Rishikesh</b>: From Delhi, you have the option to travel to
     either Dehradun or Rishikesh, both of which are starting points for the
     Brahmatal Trek.</li>
 <ul type="discd">
  <li><b>By
      Air</b>: The nearest airport is the Jolly Grant Airport in Dehradun. You
      can take a direct flight from Delhi to Dehradun. From the airport, you
      can hire a taxi or take a local bus to reach the respective trek starting
      point.</li>
  <li><b>By
      Train</b>: There are several trains that connect Delhi to Dehradun. The
      Dehradun Railway Station is the main railway station. From there, you can
      proceed to the trek starting point.</li>
  <li><b>By
      Road</b>: You can also take a bus from Delhi to Dehradun or Rishikesh.
      There are various private and state-run bus services available. Rishikesh
      is closer to Delhi compared to Dehradun, and it’s a common starting point
      for treks in the region.</li>
 </ul>
 <li><b>Rishikesh
     to Dehradun (if applicable)</b>: If you decide to start your trek from
     Dehradun, you can take a bus or taxi from Rishikesh to Dehradun. The
     distance between the two is relatively short.</li>
 <li><b>From
     Dehradun/Rishikesh to Brahmatal Trek Starting Point</b>: The trek starting
     point for Brahmatal Trek is usually Lohajung. You can follow these steps:</li>
 <ul type="discd">
  <li><b>By
      Road</b>: From Dehradun or Rishikesh, you can book a taxi or take a
      shared jeep to Lohajung. The journey takes around 8-10 hours depending on
      road conditions.</li>
 </ul>
 <li><b>Trekking
     Preparations</b>: Before embarking on the trek, make sure you have all the
     necessary trekking permits, equipment, and supplies. It’s advisable to go
     through a trekking agency that can arrange for guides, porters, and other
     logistical support.</li>
</ol>

















<p class="MsoNormalM"><b>ATM Point and Mobile Connectivity in Brahmatal Trek ?</b></p>

















<p class="MsoNormalM">The Brahmatal trek is a moderate-level trek located in the
remote areas of the Uttarakhand Himalayas, and it has limited infrastructure.
Here’s what you need to know about&nbsp;<b>ATM points</b>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<b>mobile
connectivity</b>:</p>

















<p class="MsoNormalM"><b>1.&nbsp;ATM Points:</b></p>

















<ul type="discd">
 <li>The
     last reliable ATM point for the Brahmatal trek is in&nbsp;<b>Dewal</b>, a
     small town you’ll pass through on the way to Lohajung, which is the base
     camp for the trek.</li>
 <li><b>Lohajung</b>:
     There might be a few ATMs in Lohajung, but they can be unreliable, often
     running out of cash or being out of service due to network issues. It’s
     highly advisable to withdraw sufficient cash either from&nbsp;<b>Rishikesh</b>,&nbsp;<b>Karnaprayag</b>,
     or&nbsp;<b>Dehradun</b>&nbsp;before heading to the base camp.</li>
</ul>

















<p class="MsoNormalM"><b>Tip</b>: Carry enough cash for the entire trek, including
transportation, food, and emergency expenses, as you won’t find many ATMs once
you start the trek.</p>

















<p class="MsoNormalM"><b>2.&nbsp;Mobile Connectivity:</b></p>

















<ul type="discd">
 <li><b>Lohajung
     (Base Camp)</b>: You may get basic mobile connectivity in Lohajung,
     especially for&nbsp;<b>BSNL</b>&nbsp;and sometimes&nbsp;<b>Airtel</b>&nbsp;networks.
     Other providers like Jio and Vodafone may have patchy or no network
     coverage.</li>
 <li><b>During
     the Trek</b>: Mobile connectivity is almost non-existent once you leave
     Lohajung and head deeper into the mountains. As you ascend to higher
     altitudes, you will lose signal entirely.</li>
 <li><b>Emergency
     Communication</b>: If you need to stay in touch during the trek, it’s
     advisable to inform your family before starting. In rare cases, you might
     get some weak BSNL network signals at specific high points, but it’s not
     reliable.</li>
</ul>

















<p class="MsoNormalM"><b>Important Tips:</b></p>

















<ul type="discd">
 <li><b>Download
     Offline Maps</b>: Since you won’t have mobile data during the trek, it’s a
     good idea to download offline maps of the region.</li>
 <li><b>Satellite
     Phones</b>: Some trekking agencies carry satellite phones for emergencies,
     but this is not common.</li>
 <li><b>In
     Case of Emergency</b>: Your trek leaders and local guides are usually
     well-prepared for handling emergencies in areas without mobile
     connectivity.</li>
</ul>

















<p class="MsoNormalM"><b>Summary:</b></p>

















<ul type="discd">
 <li><b>ATM</b>:
     Last reliable point is in&nbsp;<b>Dewal</b>; withdraw cash before the
     trek.</li>
 <li><b>Mobile
     Connectivity</b>: Patchy at best in&nbsp;<b>Lohajung</b>, and almost no
     connectivity during the trek (BSNL might work in some spots).</li>
</ul>

















<p class="MsoNormalM">&nbsp;</p>


















<br />                        </div>
                     </div>
